 the Middle Ages as a personal name and this may have given rise to some instances of the surname.","English: perhaps a nickname for someone who wore, made, or sold girdles, from Middle English <i>ceint</i>, <i>seint</i>, <i>saint</i> ‘girdle’ (Old French <i>ceint</i>, Latin <i>cinctum</i>). Compare   Center  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Center","meanings":["English and Scottish (Aberdeenshire): metonymic occupational name from Middle English, Old French <i>ceinture</i>, <i>seinture</i> ‘girdle’, denoting someone who made or sold girdles, or perhaps a nickname for someone who wore a distinctive girdle.","English: variant of   Senter   1.","Americanized form of German   Zehnder   or of some other similar (like-sounding) surname."]},{"name":"Sant","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Krishan, Anagha, Anjali, Arvind, Deepak, Milind, Nilima, Ravindra, Sanjeev, Sanjiv, Vasudev.","English (Cheshire and Staffordshire): variant of   Saint  .","Italian (northeastern): variant of   Santo  ."]},{"name":"Sante","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Luc, Camille, Lucien.  Spanish Alejandro, Anselmo, Carlos, Emilio, Jesusa, Jorge.","French (also <b>Santé</b>): probably a nickname for a healthy person, from French <i>santé</i> ‘good health’.","Galician, Asturian-Leonese, and Spanish (southwestern): habitational name from one of several places called Sante, in Galicia, Portugal, and Asturias, from a Visigothic personal name. This surname is also found in the Philippines."]}]},{"name":"Valéry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Colette, Pierre, Raoul, Yva.","French and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the personal name <i>Valery</i>, French form of Latin <i>Valerius</i> (see   Valerio  ).","Americanized form of Italian   Valerio   or   Valeri  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vallery","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Leonce, Monique.","French:","habitational name from Vallery in Yonne, once a Gallo-Roman estate, recorded in 1218 as <i>Valerianus</i>."]},{"name":"Valerio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Ana, Manuel, Pedro, Mario, Luis, Francisco, Ramon, Ruben, Carlos, Jesus.  Italian Antonio, Angelo, Lucio, Francesco, Maurizio, Niccolo, Romeo, Vito, Amadeo, Anastasio, Aureliano, Carmela.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Valerio</i>, from Latin <i>Valerius</i>, a Roman surname ultimately derived from Latin <i>valere</i> ‘to flourish, to be strong and healthy’. The name was borne by several early Christian saints, among them 4th-century bishops of Trier and Zaragoza and 5th-century bishops of Sorrento and of Antibes. Compare   Valery  ."]}]},{"name":"Laurette","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin.  See  <b>Laura</b>   ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Laurette Saint Valéry was born in 1163, in Normandy, France, her father, Bernard de Saint Valéry, was 47 and her mother, Anora de Dommart, was 36. She had at least 1 daughter with Aléaume de Fontaines. She died in 1190, in Aberdeen, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 27."},"et":{"1163–1190":"1163–1190","1150–1189":"1150–1189","1151–1223":"1151–1223","1155–1210":"1155–1210","1156–1191":"1156–1191","1153–1190":"1153–1190","1166–1223":"1166–1223","1173–1219":"1173–1219","–1181":"–1181","1162–1205":"1162–1205","1180–1227":"1180–1227","1117–1191":"1117–1191","1128–1194":"1128–1194","1190":"1190","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1153":"1153","1163":"1163","1162":"1162","1173":"1173","1151":"1151","1194":"1194","1150":"1150","1181":"1181","1180":"1180","1191":"1191","1128":"1128","1117":"1117","1227":"1227","1205":"1205","1223":"1223","1156":"1156","1189":"1189","1166":"1166","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","1219":"1219","Normandie, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Aberdeen, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Aberdeen,